An earlier, unfinished German-language ''Encyclopaedia Judaica'' was published by [[Nahum_Goldmann|Nahum Goldmann]]'s Eshkol Publishing Society in Berlin 1928-1934. The chief editors were [[Jakob_Klatzkin|Jakob Klatzkin]] and [[Ismar_Elbogen|Ismar Elbogen]]. Ten volumes from ''Aach'' to ''Lyra'' appeared before the project halted due to the unfavorable Nazi regime. Two Hebrew-language volumes A-Antipas were also published, under the title '''''Eshkol''''' (Hebrew אשכול). A few of the articles from the German ''Judaica'' and even some of the [[Wiedergutmachung|reparations]] payments to Goldmann were used in making the English-language ''Judaica''. A shorter Jewish Encyclopedia was published at the turn of century. (See: http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/. It was followed by the
Jüdisches Lexikon I — II. (1927 — 28) and Encyclopedia Judaica I — II (1927 — 28) and Zsidó Lexikon (1929, edited by Ujvári Péter, on Hungarian) see: http://www.zsidlex.extra.hu

The English-language ''Judaica'' is also available on [[CD-ROM|CD-ROM]]. The CD-ROM version is enhanced by at least 100,000 hyperlinks and several other features including videos, slide shows, maps, music and Hebrew pronunciations.

Because of its comprehensive scope, authority, and widespread availability, the ''Encyclopaedia Judaica'' is recommended by the [[Library_of_Congress|Library of Congress]] and by the [[Association_of_Jewish_Libraries|Association of Jewish Libraries]] for use in determining the authoritative [[romanization|romanization]] of names of Jewish authors. Its guidelines for [[romanization_of_Hebrew|transliterating Hebrew into English]] are followed by many academic books and journals.

In July 2003, [[Thomson_Gale|Thomson Gale]] announced that it acquired the rights to publish a second edition of ''Encyclopaedia Judaica'', expecting to publish in December 2006 under one of its imprints, [[Macmillan_Reference_USA|Macmillan Reference USA]]. Gale has published other substantial revisions of major reference works in the field of religion in recent years, including second editions of ''[[The_Encyclopedia_of_Religion|The Encyclopedia of Religion]]'' and ''[[The_New_Catholic_Encyclopedia|The New Catholic Encyclopedia]]''. Together with original publishers Keter Publishing House, Gale has declared its intent update of wholesale sections of ''Encyclopaedia Judaica'' for the new edition, including the entries on the [[Holocaust|Holocaust]], American Jewry, [[Israel|Israel]] and others.

[[Fred_Skolnik|Fred Skolnik]], who served as a co-editor on the original edition of ''Judaica'', has been retained as Editor-in-Chief for the 2nd edition. American Holocaust scholar [[Michael_Berenbaum|Michael Berenbaum]] serves as the editor for the Holocaust and Americana sections of the encyclopedia. It is estimated that the new edition will contain at least 22,000 articles.
